            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Karen Riley was a Daly City kid, born and raised in a small house where practicality was valued over ambition. Her father drove a bus, her mother kept the home, and the future seemed to be a pre-drawn map of steady work and Friday night fish fries. After high school, Karen followed that map, moving across the county line into San Francisco for a receptionist job and the thrill of city independence.\n\nSan Francisco, for her, began with love. In her early twenties, she met Loc Tran, a thoughtful, witty architect whose family had arrived from Vietnam in the late 70s. Marrying him wasn't just a union; it was an expansion of her entire world. He introduced her to ph\u1edf on Clement Street, the nuances of the Lunar New Year, and a perspective shaped by a history vastly different from her own. For fifteen years, they built a life in a small Inner Richmond apartment.\n\nTheir world was shattered when Loc passed away from a sudden illness, leaving Karen a widow at 38. Grief forged a new kind of resilience in her. She kept his name, a permanent anchor to the best years of her life. Needing unshakeable stability, she took a certification course and secured a position as a Medical Administrative Assistant at a university\u2019s student health center. For the past fifteen years, she has been the calm center in a storm of student anxieties and ailments, the one who knows every insurance code and can soothe a panicked freshman with a kind word.\n\nNow 53, Karen\u2019s life follows a comforting rhythm. Her day starts with the rumbling journey of the 38-Geary bus, a 5.5-mile commute she navigates with a paperback and practiced ease. She lives in the same rent-controlled apartment she shared with Loc, its windows now filled with thriving houseplants. Her social circle is small but deep, consisting of a few colleagues and her late husband\u2019s sister, with whom she still shares a weekly dinner.\n\nHer dream is no longer for a grand life, but a peaceful one. She hopes to one day visit Vietnam, to see the coastal towns Loc described so vividly. More immediately, she aspires to retire in a decade, stay in her neighborhood, and have enough saved to enjoy the city\u2019s quiet pleasures: long walks in Golden Gate Park, leisurely mornings at a local cafe, and the enduring comfort of the home she fought so hard to maintain."
