            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe was twenty-three, standing in a tiny, fog-windowed restaurant on Clement Street. Loc was patiently explaining how to tear the mint and squeeze the lime into the steaming bowl of ph\u1edf. The scent of star anise and beef broth was entirely new, a language she didn\u2019t know but suddenly understood. It wasn't just soup; it was the taste of his history, of a world so much larger than Daly City. In that moment, she knew falling in love with him meant falling in love with everything that made him.\n\n2.\nThey\u2019d been married for a year, on a foggy Saturday in their Inner Richmond apartment. Loc was sketching at the small drafting table by the window, and she was reading on their second-hand sofa. No words were exchanged, just the soft scratch of his pencil and the whisper of a turning page. Karen looked at the light catching the dust motes and felt a profound peace. This little space, filled with his quiet ambition and their shared silence, was the first place that truly felt like her own home.\n\n3.\nThe week after the funeral, the casseroles stopped arriving. Karen stood alone in the apartment, Loc\u2019s house slippers still by the door. She saw his half-finished cup of tea on the coaster, a pale ring now permanently stained. The silence was an active, crushing force. In that deafening quiet, a terrifying clarity struck her: no one was coming to fix this. Survival was now entirely up to her. It was the moment grief hardened into a cold, fierce resolve to simply endure.\n\n4.\nHer first month at the student health center, a freshman was having a panic attack over his insurance coverage. Her supervisor was flustered, but Karen felt a strange calm. She spoke to the boy, her voice low and even, and walked him through the codes she had spent months memorizing. Seeing the relief wash over his face, she felt something shift inside her. This wasn't just a job; it was proof she could build a shelter for herself, and even be a small shelter for others.\n\n5.\nJust last Sunday, she was watering her houseplants. She misted a thriving monstera, a cutting from Loc\u2019s sister, and remembered how Loc used to joke that he could kill a plant with a single glance. A soft, genuine smile touched her lips. The memory didn't tear at her; it was just a warm, familiar stone in the garden of her life. The sun streamed through the glass, the 38-Geary rumbled past below, and she felt a quiet, rooted happiness. This was enough."
